  _legacyStoryId: story_zombie_special
  storySegments:
  - storyId: story_zombie_official_seg1
    requiredItem: {fileID: 11400000, guid: dc4dd4bb1dc85eb448c9376aca1f71e2, type: 2}
    storySummary: "The moment the book was opened, memories spread like a map: he
      had been an imperial surveyor, sent to chart the realm with compass, rods,
      and ink. He crossed mountain passes, salt marshes, empty plains, and frontier
      posts\u2014measuring rivers, towns, and strategic routes, while noting local
      customs and the hollow faces of famine years. The Travel Chronicle was his
      report to the court, but also his proof that he had been there, seen the world,
      and set it down in words."
  - storyId: story_zombie_official_seg2
    requiredItem: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 89a56ffcc89f1174e91e65140ca29d00, type: 2}
    storySummary: "The sugar-coated hawthorn had long since soured and hardened,
      its red dulled like sweetness frozen in time. It revealed the other half of
      his story: always on the road, never sure of his return, he bought a skewer
      at every market to bring home\u2014something for the children, and a quiet
      \u201CI\u2019m back\u201D for his wife. But his routes were constantly diverted
      and cut short by war; the treat melted in rain, shattered by the saddle, or
      never made it past the next dispatch. In the world\u2019s last days he died
      stranded in another province, clutching that undelivered sweetness like an
      apology that came too late."
  dialogueConversationTitle: ZombieOfficial
  shortDescription: "Near the ruined post road, a zombie in tattered official robes
    has been seen\u2014cuffs worn white, a broken surveyor\u2019s case at its waist.
    It doesn\u2019t lunge like the others; it paces the crossroads, staring at the
    ground and tracing measurements in the dirt as if mapping a road that\u2019s
    gone. If you get close, you may catch its hoarse mutter: mountains, post stations,
    ferries, boundary stones\u2014names from a world long past."
